Welcome to the=C2=A0868=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined u=
s since last Tuesday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0184,121 =
smart, curious folks by subscribing here:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Tuesday!=20
It=E2=80=99s a great week over here at Not Boring HQ. The Eagles are back i=
n the Super Bowl and I get to write about one of my favorite companies: Wan=
der [ https://substack.com/redirect/b6bafa61-c458-4320-b2e8-d42873795923?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Wander has a chance to build one of those iconic brands that becomes both n=
oun and verb. As they grow their portfolio of incredible vacation rental pr=
operties throughout the US and beyond, I suspect that =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99=
s Wander=E2=80=9D will become synonymous with =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s get aw=
ay for the week.=E2=80=9D=20
Building that kind of brand, especially when Airbnb and established hotel c=
hains exist, is really hard. It takes a relentless attention to detail, a r=
are willingness to do everything in-house, and an uncommon ability to fit a=
ll of the pieces together just so. It also takes the capital to achieve ubi=
quity, which is why Wander recently launched Atlas [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/b421ebed-ac01-476c-82a3-366442991f3e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the first vacation rental REIT.=20
So this is a piece about Wander, but it=E2=80=99s also a case study on how =
to build a Natively Integrated Company from the ground up. We=E2=80=99ve wr=
itten that the most important companies of the next decade will be built at=
 the intersection of Bits & Atoms =E2=80=94 Wander provides a playbook for =
those willing and able to do the hard work.=20
This essay is a Sponsored Deep Dive on a Not Boring Capital portfolio compa=
ny. You can read more about how I choose which companies to do deep dives o=
n, and how I write them here [ https://substack.com/redirect/dbf6159b-fbb3-=
4c4a-a51b-bc5ff1b13403?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Nothing in this essay is investment advice - check the fo=
otnote.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Wander: Owning Happy Places
Not all those who wander are lost.
Look, I didn=E2=80=99t want to use that quote, but bear with me.=C2=A0
Since J.R.R. Tolkien first wrote those words in The Riddle of Strider, they=
=E2=80=99ve been splashed across so many inspirational posters and Instagra=
m bios that they=E2=80=99ve become meaningless.
Worse than meaningless, in fact. Tolkien meant the exact opposite. The orig=
inal is a reference to Aragorn, who wanders around his kingdom not because =
he is lost, but because he has a very specific goal: to learn to become a g=
reat ruler. Those who wander with a purpose, according to Tolkien, are not =
lost. Those who wander aimlessly are.=C2=A0
Admittedly, I only looked into the history of that quote because this is a =
piece about a company called Wander [ https://substack.com/redirect/b6bafa6=
1-c458-4320-b2e8-d42873795923?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. But as I read this explanation [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/28e854cf-abc7-4711-94d4-8fe2e417f34b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], it struck me that the dueling =
interpretations of that same quote are a perfect metaphor for Wander and Ai=
rbnb.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Wander is vertically integrated and purposeful; Airbnb is a more meandering=
 marketplace.
You=E2=80=99ve heard of Airbnb, probably stayed in a few, and maybe even li=
sted your home. I have, and I=E2=80=99ve had good, if varied, experiences. =
I=E2=80=99ve stayed in some Airbnbs that were more wonderful than the pictu=
res and descriptions could have conveyed, and some that were more appalling=
 than the Host would have wanted us to believe. Airbnb is a marketplace, an=
d navigating a marketplace can feel like aimlessly wandering.=C2=A0
For a long time, Airbnb had that special startup sheen on it that glossed o=
ver the inconsistencies. Sometimes, you=E2=80=99d show up to an Airbnb and =
the door was locked and the host didn=E2=80=99t answer the phone and you=E2=
=80=99d be stuck outside in a foreign country for hours. Sometimes the beds=
 were barely made. Often, the pictures looked just a little bit better than=
 the real thing.=C2=A0
When people booked Airbnbs, all of the little hiccups became part of the ad=
venture. =E2=80=9CRemember when we were stranded outside our Airbnb in the =
rain in Porto for three hours and we found that amazing little bar next doo=
r?!=E2=80=9D That was part of the fun! Not all those who wander are lost, a=
nd we were ~wAnDeRiNg~!=C2=A0
Now, however, Airbnb is a public and well-known company, and the little inc=
onsistencies aren=E2=80=99t as much fun as they used to be. The beds aren=
=E2=80=99t as comfortable as hotel beds. There=E2=80=99s no food in the fri=
dge. The Host charged me a $300 cleaning fee and made me take out the trash=
? Tweets and videos like this one are more and more common:
Wander, on the other hand, feels purposeful in every detail.=C2=A0
If you haven=E2=80=99t heard of Wander, the best way to think of it is as a=
 vertically-integrated Airbnb. If you haven=E2=80=99t seen Wander, the prop=
erties are ridiculous. Here=E2=80=99s a little eye candy:
You should go check out the properties and the video tours for each on its =
site [ https://substack.com/redirect/b6bafa61-c458-4320-b2e8-d42873795923?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. After =
I mentioned to Puja that I was writing this piece, she watched all of them =
back-to-back. Wander properties are architectural gems in stunning location=
s =E2=80=93 some have warnings not to bring kids because they=E2=80=99re pe=
rched on the edges of cliffs. They=E2=80=99re the kind of properties that c=
an cost over $1,000 per night =E2=80=93 don=E2=80=99t worry, you can split =
with friends or teammates in the app =E2=80=93 and still reach occupancy ra=
tes in the 80-90% range and higher.=C2=A0
In order to craft a perfect experience, the company handles everything itse=
lf:=C2=A0
Acquisitions. Its team scours the country for architecturally stunning vaca=
tion properties in unique locations and purchases them.
Design. Wander renovates homes and outfits them with products and furniture=
 from top brands (every rental comes with a Tesla, for example).
Booking. All properties are listed on the Wander website and app, where gue=
sts can book them for themselves, family and friends, or Teams [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/3d2c804c-d596-46b9-bc18-09f783156a90?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Bookers are able to inv=
ite guests and even split costs from within the app.=C2=A0
Property Management: Wander=E2=80=99s team operates each property in-house =
to keep the experience bar high for each guest.=C2=A0
The benefit of that approach is that it translates into a consistently high=
-quality experience. Wander=E2=80=99s Customer Satisfaction Score is consis=
tently in the 90s. The drawback is that, unlike Airbnb which is able to acq=
uire its supply for free and scale at near-internet speed, Wander is more e=
xpensive and slower to scale. Acquiring, renovating, and furnishing propert=
ies is neither cheap nor easy.=C2=A0
Or rather, it was capital intensive until very recently, when it launched A=
tlas [ https://substack.com/redirect/061fa4eb-3adb-4d65-958d-7267b77886bf?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
In my Fund III announcement [ https://substack.com/redirect/fa7fcf85-cd7f-4=
41e-b696-3f2216571130?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I highlighted Wander specifically:
We=E2=80=99ve backed a number of companies in traditionally capital-intensi=
ve categories with the ability to scale in a capital efficient manner. As o=
ne example from our Fund II portfolio, Wander [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/b6bafa61-c458-4320-b2e8-d42873795923?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which is a vertically integrated vacatio=
n rental home company, just launched Atlas [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
061fa4eb-3adb-4d65-958d-7267b77886bf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the =E2=80=9Cworld=E2=80=99s first vacation=
 rental REIT,=E2=80=9D to scale its portfolio without dilutive venture fund=
ing.
With Atlas [ https://substack.com/redirect/061fa4eb-3adb-4d65-958d-7267b778=
86bf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
Wander is able to move the costs of acquiring, renovating, and furnishing i=
ts real estate portfolio off of its balance sheet by selling shares in its =
portfolio of homes to institutional and accredited investors. And investors=
 get access to a new asset class =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9Cthe first and only vaca=
tion rental REIT (as far as we know)=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 with a targeted 8% =
annual dividend. Importantly, Wander retains full control of the experience=
 as it manages all properties in the Atlas portfolio.=C2=A0
What Wander is doing with Atlas is catnip to me. It=E2=80=99s a marriage of=
 my professional experience (better executed) with ideas I=E2=80=99ve been =
thinking through for a long time:
Natively Integrated Company [ https://substack.com/redirect/dfeb018e-39d4-4=
82b-bbb1-a09a15955393?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=C2=A0
Zillbnb [ https://substack.com/redirect/52f00e69-4dca-4ef0-9397-bbcbd36e051=
b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
While I believe that the natively-integrated approach is the only way to at=
tack a category dominated by large marketplaces, which we=E2=80=99ll discus=
s, the company=E2=80=99s strategy really comes into focus with Atlas.=C2=A0
During my first meeting with Wander CEO John Andrew Entwistle [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/9bf460bc-707d-48d7-9318-dda75e94c410?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a Thiel Fellow and secon=
d-time founder, it all clicked. It was the pitch I was born to swing at, an=
d I immediately invested one of Not Boring Capital=E2=80=99s larger Fund II=
 checks. My only regret one year later is that I didn=E2=80=99t invest more=
=2E=C2=A0
Over the past year, I=E2=80=99ve seen Wander execute at every level, from t=
he obvious product-related things to all the little details. Its investor u=
pdates are among my favorites to receive because each team leader writes hi=
s or her team=E2=80=99s section. I=E2=80=99m writing this wearing my Wander=
 sweatshirt, the most comfortable I own. When I asked JAE where he got them=
, he told me they designed them in-house, down to the fabric selection, bec=
ause the quality of the others they looked at didn=E2=80=99t meet their sta=
ndards.=C2=A0
Now, they=E2=80=99re bringing that same attention to detail to bear on Atla=
s. With Atlas, Wander is creating a new asset class =E2=80=93 short-term re=
ntal REITs (Real Estate Investment Trust). The company spent roughly $1 mil=
lion to bring the product to market, working with firms like Latham & Watki=
ns, Ernst & Young, and Citrin Cooperman. They structured the product as a R=
eg D REIT instead of a Reg A offering. They poured months of effort interna=
lly =E2=80=93 led by JAE, VP Finance & Head of Acquisitions David Molotsky =
(ex-Goldman Real Estate), and Head of Capital Markets Jake Kelley (ex-Morga=
n Stanley Real Estate Structured Finance) =E2=80=93 into getting it right. =
The Private Placement Memorandum =E2=80=93 which you=E2=80=99ll have the pl=
easure of reading during the subscription process =E2=80=93 is 160 pages lo=
ng and chock full of detail. It doesn=E2=80=99t feel like a two-year-old st=
artup led by a 25-year-old founder did this.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s all part of the master plan =E2=80=93 a purposeful wander =E2=
=80=93 that JAE laid out the first time we spoke.
Prove that Wander can acquire and manage the top short-term rentals on its =
own balance sheet.=C2=A0
Build a brand and an integrated machine to do it repeatedly and predictably=
=2E
Build an investment product that gives people the opportunity to invest in =
the properties they love while letting Wander scale in a capital-efficient =
manner.=C2=A0
Today, we=E2=80=99ll analyze that strategy, tour Wander=E2=80=99s portfolio=
, dive into the details on Atlas, and discuss where the company might go fr=
om here:
Zillbnb and the Short-Term Arbitrage
Natively Integrated Vacation Rentals
Wander Atlas
Wandering Into the Future=C2=A0
To understand Wander=E2=80=99s potential, you need to understand the theory=
 behind building a portfolio of STR properties. To do that, we=E2=80=99ll s=
tart by imagining that Airbnb and Zillow had a baby.=C2=A0
Zillbnb and the Short-Term Arbitrage
In June 2020, I wrote a Fantasy M&A piece proposing that Zillow and Airbnb =
should merge. I gave five reasons I thought a combined =E2=80=9CZillbnb=E2=
=80=9D could make sense, the most relevant of which for this piece is that =
combining Zillow=E2=80=99s Offers iBuyer product and Airbnb=E2=80=99s short=
-term rental expertise would create a more robust business. I wrote:=C2=A0
Plugging in Airbnb would lower Zillow=E2=80=99s risk and improve its yields=
=2E Instead of a binary outcome - buy the=
 house for $x and only profit if Zil=
low can sell the house for $x+y - Zillow could turn on short-term rentals t=
o generate income while looking for a buyer at the right price.=C2=A0
Zillow may even choose to continue to operate the homes it buys as short-te=
rm rentals on Airbnb instead of selling, based on predictive calculations o=
f which offering will produce higher yields. Short-term rentals can generat=
e 30% higher rates [ https://substack.com/redirect/d3f287ca-25d2-461c-b3cd-=
0d7ef1a6fe38?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] than long-term rentals. Airbnb has even shown a desire to own and ma=
nage its own supply with Backyard [ https://substack.com/redirect/2e5c6f7a-=
dec1-4bbd-a3eb-1d3178cfff45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
Zillbnb has the opportunity to build something more potent than Blackstone=
=E2=80=99s Invitation Homes [ https://substack.com/redirect/561ba661-693a-4=
a04-b66c-60b7051882bd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ], on which the private equity firm netted about $7 billion b=
y buying up a portfolio of single-family homes in the US and managing them =
as rental properties. By using Zillbnb=E2=80=99s combined data, the company=
 can make sharper offers based on both short-term and rental cashflow predi=
ctions. By offering Zillow Offers homes for one night, one month, one year,=
 or forever, Zillbnb would be able to optimize yields based on where each d=
uration prices in each market.
Joining forces with Airbnb might even increase the buyer pool for Zillow=E2=
=80=99s homes. Selling homes with Airbnb up and running turns a home into a=
 turnkey small business, making it attractive to financial buyers looking f=
or yield in a low interest rate environment.
That=E2=80=99s a longer block quote than Dan [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/03854bd1-2eee-408a-99c6-31f08606f4c8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] normally lets me get away with, but it=E2=
=80=99s important context for thinking about Wander=E2=80=99s portfolio. Es=
sentially, acquiring properties that the company expects to appreciate, fin=
ancing them, and offering them as short-term rentals increases optionality,=
 potentially lowering risk and improving yields compared to a standard iBuy=
er model and compared to a portfolio of single-family rentals (SFRs).
In the iBuyer model, like Zillow=E2=80=99s now-defunct Offers or Opendoor, =
companies acquire properties, do improvements, and attempt to sell them qui=
ckly, taking a small spread on very large numbers. If the market turns, or =
a home takes longer than expected to sell, however, the company is stuck ho=
lding the bag. By introducing short-term rentals into the mix, they could g=
enerate revenue and buy themselves time to wait for the right sale price.=
=C2=A0=C2=A0
The first time John Andrew told me the plan for Wander, I immediately saw t=
he Zillbnb dream, but on a longer timescale. Instead of buying to flip, Wan=
der would acquire properties that it expects to appreciate over a decade or=
 so. It mainly buys residential homes, not those that are already operating=
 as short-term rentals, which means that it can often acquire homes for les=
s than they=E2=80=99re worth to the company. By building a diversified port=
folio of high-quality STRs in different locations, it can reduce risk and i=
mprove yields across the portfolio.=C2=A0
In real estate terms, Wander is buying residential homes and converting the=
m into their =E2=80=9Chighest and best use=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0 short-term renta=
ls.=C2=A0 By converting them to STRs and improving them cost-effectively, t=
hey can then be valued based on a =E2=80=9Ccap rate=E2=80=9D applied to the=
 cash flow they generate, rather than appraised as a residential home. The =
cap rate is the Net Operating Income (NOI) the property generates each year=
 divided by the Purchase Price of the home, and a lower cap rate is general=
ly a sign that the property is a lower risk investment.=C2=A0
So for illustrative purposes, if Wander buys ten $1 million homes that the =
market believes it could rent annually for $100k above its costs, it would =
be buying at a 10% cap rate =E2=80=93 $100k/$1 million =E2=80=93 for a tota=
l of $10 million. If it=E2=80=99s able to increase its NOI to $150k on each=
 of the properties and sell the portfolio at the same cap rate =E2=80=93 10=
% =E2=80=93 it could sell the portfolio for $15 million, or a 50% profit. I=
f, by lowering risk through diversification and professionalization, it can=
 lower the cap rate the purchaser is willing to pay to 8%, it can sell the =
portfolio for $18.75 million, or an 87.5% profit.=C2=A0=C2=A0
If Wander is able to accelerate the institutionalization of the STR market,=
 time may bring lower cap rates as the market matures. The larger and more =
sophisticated an industry becomes, the more likely it is to attract large p=
ools of investors that generally seek low-risk, lower-yielding investments.=
 As a very relevant comp, institutionalization of the SFR market over the p=
ast decade or so, and the billions of dollars invested in the space, have d=
riven cap rates down from 10% to ~6%.=C2=A0
Wander=E2=80=99s returns may be further enhanced if you factor in annual re=
venue growth and the fact that Wander finances its properties, meaning that=
 it might take out a mortgage for 60-75% of the purchase price and only put=
 down 25-40% in cash. If it can cover its mortgage payments and operating c=
osts, it can produce higher levered returns than it could by paying the who=
le purchase price in cash.=C2=A0
Up to this point, there=E2=80=99s not a huge difference between the STR mod=
el and the SFR model aside from the fact that SFR has been institutionalize=
d, lowering cap rates. The STR market today is where the SFR=C2=A0 market w=
as roughly a decade ago. A professional SFR operator like Invitation Homes =
can purchase a diverse portfolio of residential properties, standardize the=
m, rent them on an annual basis to cover its costs and generate NOI, and se=
ll the lower-risk portfolio at a lower cap rate. Like Wander, an SFR operat=
or can choose to rent out properties when the numbers favor renting, and se=
ll them when the numbers favor selling.=C2=A0
Here, though, Wander=E2=80=99s ability to rent properties short-term, for a=
s little as three nights, gives them more optionality, and the opportunity =
to further increase NOI versus SFRs.=C2=A0
As short-term rentals are the highest and best use, optionality provides do=
wnside protection. STRs typically generate more income than SFRs, but STRs =
can also be rented long-term (like SFR=E2=80=99s) if a particular home does=
n=E2=80=99t perform well as an STR. The opposite is not true. Further, as a=
 backup to the backup, a Wander STR could be converted back into a regular =
residential home if it isn=E2=80=99t performing as an STR or didn=E2=80=99t=
 convert well into an STR. That backup backup market =E2=80=93 the US singl=
e-family home market =E2=80=93 is the largest, and one of the most liquid, =
marketplaces in the world.
For now, though, Wander is able to generate a higher NOI by renting its pro=
perties to guests for a few nights at a time. Its focus is on increasing Re=
vPAR =E2=80=93 a hospitality industry metric based on Average Daily Rate (A=
DR) and occupancy =E2=80=93 by continuing to improve the quality of the gue=
st experience and making sure its properties are booked as many nights as p=
ossible. It=E2=80=99s able to do both of those things better than a pure ma=
rketplace could because it=E2=80=99s a Natively Integrated Company.
To read how Wander is building a Natively Integrated Vacation Rental Compan=
y, learn more about Atlas, and glimpse into Wander=E2=80=99s future=E2=80=
=A6
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/03854bd1-2eee-408a-99c6-31f08=
606f4c8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing, and to JAE, Jake, Kyle, David, and Dom for your input!
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your podcast feed on=
 Thursday and back in your inbox on Friday for the Weekly Dose.=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

